{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_012DbfkrXsNmwKi2bg5PbDZu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. Iteration 28 implemented ALL 4 fixes from the iteration 27 plan, but the score didn't change (90.1%). The same 11 failures persist. Let me analyze why each fix didn't work:\n\n1. **Blind OCR repair (Pattern 1, 5 cases)**: The fix was implemented - `applyBlindOcrRepair` is applied to early-position candidates. But `Braised Cod with White Wine` still returns empty, `Drożdże Sernik` still returns `Podaw4ć letni lub chłodny.`, etc. The blind repair probably works for straightforward cases but the remaining failures may have more complex corruption patterns (like `¡` for `i` in mixed case).\n\n\n2. **Direct-successor bonus (Pattern 2, 3 cases)**: Implemented, but `Halibut` still extracts an instruction line, `Roasted Asparagus` still extracts the description, `Ogórkowa Zupa` still returns empty. The bonus may not be strong enough, or the header detection isn't matching these specific patterns.\n3. **Multi-line dedup protection (Pattern 3, 1 case)**: Partially working - `Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables` now extracts both the short and full versions, which is progress but still not the clean single-line result I was aiming for.\n4. **Spillover detection (Pattern 4, 2 cases)**: `Mushroom Risotto` still extracts `CARPACCIO DI PESCE SPADA`, `Peach Cobbler` still extracts the assembly line, and `Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi` with mixed-case OCR also fails.\n\nLooking at the detailed results, `Lemon Herb Roasted Vegetables` is now passing but the output shows duplication—both the single-line and multi-line versions made it through, so the deduplication logic isn't fully working.\n\nIteration 28 had mixed results overall: the multi-line pattern got fixed but with that duplication issue, while OCR errors, section headers, and spillover cases remain broken across 11 total failures. ytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi is the rest of that dish name. Looking at the pattern breakdown, I see that iteration 28 fixed the multi-line split issue from iteration 27, but introduced a new mixed-case OCR error instead. The total failure count stayed at 11, just with different error categories—Pattern 3 shifted from multi-line splits to missing titles, while Pattern 4 changed from previous page issues to mixed-case OCR problems.\n\nThe real problem is that the fixes from iteration 27 didn't actually address the root causes. The blind repair for OCR errors might not be matching the actual corruption patterns, or the repaired text still fails downstream validation. The header pattern fixes similarly didn't resolve their underlying issues. I need to dig deeper into why these approaches aren't working and develop more targeted solutions. The mixed-case corruption like `KoPyTka` gets caught by the OCR repair for individual characters but the erratic capitalization still causes the text to embed poorly and fail matching. The real insight here is that all 11 remaining failures are on synthetic test files—the system works perfectly on actual user photos. So the question becomes whether chasing these generated edge cases is worth the effort, though the user clearly wants improvement. I'm starting to think the core problem is that corrupted or mispositioned titles just don't embed well enough, and the position heuristics alone can't compensate when the fallback grabs garbage instead.\n\nThe key realization is that I should focus on making garbage candidates score worse rather than just making the true title score better. For generated files especially, position should be a much stronger signal since titles are almost always near the top—but the current position bonus is barely moving the needle. For the OCR corruption cases, the blind repair approach seems sound in theory but clearly isn't working in practice, so I need to dig into why the patterns aren't firing or if the repairs themselves are producing invalid text. For the section header cases, the direct-successor bonus helps but isn't enough, so I should explore making the section header detection trigger a stronger rejection of non-matching candidates.\n\nFor spillover cases, I'm thinking it's better to focus on negative signals—if a candidate is ALL_CAPS with no corroboration and seems linguistically out of place, reject it outright. Mixed-case OCR corruption could be handled by normalizing erratic casing before scoring. The real question is whether I should be reading the actual test files to understand what's happening, but since I'm writing a spec rather than debugging, I need to think about what a fundamentally better approach would look like.\n\nInstead of just adding bonuses and extra candidates, maybe the issue is that the current system doesn't distinguish where the title actually lives in the document. I'm considering a two-pass architecture: first, identify the \"title region\" by skipping recognized preamble and focusing on the first few non-preamble lines, then within that region, apply embedding scoring with a strong position bias favoring earlier content. This separates the \"where\" problem from the \"which candidate\" problem.\n\nBut wait—this is basically what `findBurstEnd` and position bonuses already attempt to do, so the real question is why those mechanisms aren't catching the 11 failures. I need to look at the actual test cases to understand what's going wrong.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3471,"cache_read_input_tokens":41218,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3471},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b1b8cabe-82af-4d43-a6df-d4a8ec65d151","uuid":"cbc45f0e-03b2-47c3-95af-512b947c04a2"}
