{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AZyZ7rpJhqY8EoGPXzD11M","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a very clear picture of each failing case. Let me analyze why the iteration 28 fixes didn't work:\n\n**Pattern 1: OCR digit corruption (5 cases)**\n\n`Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne` - Line 1. \n- `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` is `/[0-9¡Íí€]/` which matches digits 0-9. The line has `1` characters, so it matches.\n- `applyBlindOcrRepair` on mixed case: splits by spaces, for each token, replaces `(?<=[a-zà-ż])1` → `l` and `1(?=[a-zà-ż])` → `l`. \n\n\n- When I trace through the regex replacements, `Bra1sed` gets hit by the first pattern which converts the `1` between lowercase letters into `l`, but then the second pattern also tries to fire on what's left, causing overlapping replacements that produce `Bralssed` instead of the intended `Braised`.\n\nI'm realizing the issue: both regex patterns are trying to handle the same `1`, but they're interfering with each other rather than working in sequence. I see the real problem now — `Bralsed` isn't a word at all, so the blind repair is fundamentally broken for mixed-case text. The function always maps `1` to `l`, but sometimes it should be `i` instead, like in `Braised`. For all-caps text it uses `I` which works visually, but for mixed case this 50/50 guessing approach fails half the time. I need to generate both possibilities instead of picking one.\n\nThe better approach is to try both `l` and `i` substitutions and see which one produces a valid dictionary word, or at minimum generate both candidates and let downstream filtering handle it. Even if the repair worked perfectly though, I should verify the repaired text would actually pass the hard filters — checking word count, capitalization, and whether it looks like metadata.\n\nLet me trace through the actual pipeline: the corrupted text gets passed to `repairOcrText`, which does dictionary-based repair, but if those common words aren't in the food dictionary, the digits stay. Then `passesHardFilters` runs, and I suspect `isLikelyGarbled` is catching the digits and rejecting the line before it even gets a chance to be repaired properly. The real problem is that the blind OCR repair is converting `1` to `l` when it should be converting to `i` in these cases—`Bra1sed` should become `Braised`, not `Bralsed`. The function only handles certain patterns and misses the context where `1` actually represents a misread `i`.\n\nNow looking at the \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\" example, the file structure has `FISH & SEAFOOD` as the first line, which might be a category label. I'm trying to figure out whether this gets filtered out—it's not in the standard section labels like INGREDIENTS or DIRECTIONS, and I need to check what's actually in the `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` to see if it matches.\n\nThe real puzzle is why the extractor returned a cooking instruction like \"In same pan, sauté shallots until softened\" instead of the actual title. The word \"sauté\" should trigger the cooking instruction filter, so something's off with how that's being evaluated.\n\nLooking at the word count, \"In same pan sauté shallots until softened\" is only 7 words, which means it slips under the 8-word minimum threshold that would normally filter it out. And since the line starts with \"In\" rather than a cooking verb, the hard filter doesn't catch it either. The direct-successor bonus doesn't apply here either since the previous line is blank, not a header.\n\nI'm realizing the core issue: the direct-successor bonus is checking the immediately preceding line, but when there's a blank line between a header and a recipe title, that bonus never triggers. The fix needs to look at the nearest non-blank line instead of just position-1. The same problem appears with \"Ogórkowa Zupa\" — the header line contains pipe characters which get filtered out by the hard filters, and the blank line below it prevents the bonus from activating.\n\nNow I'm wondering if `isLikelyGarbled` is filtering out \"Ogórkowa Zupa\" because of the non-ASCII character `Ó`, or if something else is causing it to return empty despite passing the other checks.\n\nFor the Mushroom Risotto case, the file structure shows cooking instructions at the start that should trigger `findBurstEnd` — lines beginning with verbs like \"Reduce\" and \"Season\" are clearly cooking instructions, so the pattern matching should catch this as a recipe burst.\n\nBut looking at the actual logic: line 0 matches the cooking verb pattern, but line 1 starts with lowercase \"creamy\" which breaks the consecutive count at j=1. Since we need j>=3 to skip the preamble, we only get j=1, so `findBurstEnd` doesn't skip anything. The prose prologue check also fails because line 0 starts with uppercase \"R\", not lowercase. So `findBurstEnd` returns 0, treating the entire file as one recipe, which means `CARPACCIO DI PESCE` gets lumped in with the Mushroom Risotto content.\n\nFor the Peach Cobbler case, the overflow marker detection should trigger on the corrupted text at the start, skip to the `---` separator, and find the actual recipe title. But instead it's extracting assembly instructions, which suggests the burst detection isn't working as expected after the separator. the overflow detection is working, but the extracted content is coming from within the PEACH COBBLER section itself—there's an \"Assembly\" subsection there that's being pulled instead of the spillover text. I need to examine the full file structure to understand where the boundary actually lies and refine the extraction logic accordingly.\n\nNow I'm identifying the core issues: the OCR repair is converting `1` to `l` when it should use `i`, the direct-successor bonus isn't accounting for blank lines between headers and titles, and the spillover detection isn't catching cases where the overflow starts with a capitalized instruction line rather than