{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018vQGpW5WHiJE7fWr9vcPA4","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a very clear picture. Let me analyze each failure and its root cause:\n\n**Pattern 1: OCR digit-for-letter (5 cases) + Pattern 4: Mixed-case OCR (1 case)**\n\nAll 6 OCR failures share the same root cause: the blind repair function maps `1→l` instead of `1→i` in mixed case. But there's a deeper issue:\n\nLooking at `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`:\n- `repairOcrText` (dictionary-based) doesn't repair because `Braised`, `with`, `White`, `Wine` might not be in `FOOD_DICTIONARY`\n\n\n- The corrupted text passes `passesHardFilters` because it clears the length check, doesn't look like an ingredient, doesn't start with a number, and isn't obviously metadata or a cooking instruction — but I need to verify what `isLikelyGarbled` actually does, since that's the real gatekeeper here.\n\nLooking at the digit ratio in `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne` — about 14% of characters are digits, which might or might not cross whatever threshold the function uses. The pattern across the test cases is interesting: the corrupted title produces no extraction, but other corrupted inputs like `Drożdże Sernik` and `Żurek Krakowski` do extract body lines, suggesting the hard filters aren't consistently blocking garbled text.\n\nThe real issue is that `1` needs context-aware replacement. In English, `1` typically becomes `i` in patterns like `Bra1sed`, `w1th`, `Wh1te`, and `W1ne`, but it becomes `l` in cases like `fillet` or `salt`. The current approach just maps everything to `l` regardless of position or surrounding characters, which explains why the blind repair produces such poor embeddings.\n\nTo fix this, I need to generate both `i` and `l` variants when encountering `1` in mixed-case positions, or better yet, default to `i` since that's far more common in recipe text. I also need to address the direct-successor bonus logic to look at the nearest non-empty line instead of just the previous position, and fix the instruction-prologue detection in `findBurstEnd` to handle cases where cooking instructions are interrupted by prose descriptions before resuming again.\n\nFor the Peach Cobbler issue, I'm realizing the problem might be with how lines starting with non-cooking-verb words like \"Assembly\" are being filtered. The line \"Assembly: 1. Preheat oven to 375°F (I90°C)\" doesn't end with a colon, so it passes that filter, but \"Assembly\" itself isn't recognized as a cooking verb, and I need to trace through the word count and filtering logic to see why it's appearing in the output when it shouldn't be. I'm realizing the hard filters are applied to the joined result, not individual lines—so `Assembly:` alone would fail, but when combined with the next line it might pass since the join wouldn't end with a colon. Now I need to check whether the overflow detection regex actually matches the corrupted text marker in the Peach Cobbler file. I see the issue now — the overflow marker pattern is too restrictive and doesn't match the actual corrupted text format. When `findBurstEnd` runs through its checks, the garbled line detector and prose prologue detector both fail to catch this malformed line, so it slips through undetected.\n\nThen `passesHardFilters` catches the bracketed text and filters it out, but the subsequent lines like \"Ingredients (continued):\" get filtered by the colon ending, and the ingredient lines starting with dashes trigger their own filter. The `isTitleAbsentPage` check is examining these filtered results to determine if the page structure is valid. I'm wondering if `PEACH COBBLER` is getting filtered out because it appears after line 21, and with the 25-candidate cap, earlier spillover lines might be pushing it past the limit. The spillover marker itself gets filtered by the regex pattern, and ingredient lines starting with dashes are also being removed, so I need to trace through which candidates actually make it through.\n\nLooking at the instruction lines, `Cream together...` starts with a cooking verb that's in the filter list, so that gets removed. Same with `Bake at 180°C...` and `Let cool completely...` — both start with cooking verbs. But `This dessert keeps in an airtight...` starts with `This`, which isn't a cooking verb, so it might survive the filter despite being an instruction line.\n\nThe separator `---` is exactly 3 characters, which technically passes the length check, but it's likely caught by the garbled text filter. Meanwhile, `PEACH COBBLER` in all caps with just 2 words should pass through as a valid candidate, even though there are many filtered lines in the spillover section before it.\n\nLooking at the actual output though, something seems off—the result shows `Assembly: 1. Preheat oven to 375°F` winning over `PEACH COBBLER`, which shouldn't happen if the embedding for a clean, short all-caps title is working correctly. The format suggests the left side is the expected title and the right side is what was extracted, so there's a mismatch somewhere in how these candidates are being ranked.\n\nI think the issue might be in how the joining process works. When lines are merged together, the hard filters get applied to the joined result rather than individual lines. So `Assembly:` alone would fail the filter for ending with a colon, but when it's joined with the next line to form `Assembly: 1. Preheat oven to 375°F`, that combined string passes through because it doesn't trigger any of the hard filter rules. The repair and joining logic is combining text from consecutive lines before the filters evaluate them. Let me recount the tokens more carefully—splitting by whitespace gives me seven words, which stays under the eight-word threshold. The text ends with a parenthesis rather than a colon, so that filter doesn't catch it either. It looks like this line survives the hard filters and moves on to embedding and scoring.\n\nNow I'm wondering why the Assembly instruction line would score higher than \"PEACH COBBLER\" when the latter should have a much stronger title similarity and gets the all-caps bonus. Maybe there's something else filtering out the peach cobbler line, or the scoring threshold isn't calibrated right. Actually, looking back at the bracketed text filter—that first line with the corrupted text is fully enclosed in brackets, so it should get caught there.\n\nBut I'm realizing the real issue might be timing. The results I'm seeing could be from before the iteration 28 changes were actually applied, and the commit message is confusing about which iteration it actually represents.\n\nLooking at the git history, commit `1ac016c` is labeled \"iteration 27\" but it's stored in the 28-1ac016c directory. The iter.txt file shows both iterations 27 and 28 scored 90.1%, which means the commit message refers to the plan number, not the evaluation run number. So the results in that directory ARE from the current code with all four fixes applied—they just didn't help.\n\nNow I need to think through why each case is still failing, starting with Peach Cobbler. I need to actually trace through the code more carefully or accept that I need to debug it. For the improvement plan, I should focus on what I CAN reason about and propose approaches that are more robust.\n\nLet me focus on writing the plan now. I have enough information about the root causes.\n\n**Summary of root causes (verified by reading test files):**\n\n1. **OCR blind repair `1→l` bug (5 cases)**: `applyBlindOcrRepair` maps `1→l` in mixed case, but for words like `Bra1sed`, `w1th`, `Wh1te`, `W1ne`, the correct mapping is `1→i`. This produces garbled text (`Bralsed`) that embeds poorly. The ALL_CAPS path correctly maps `1→I` (works for both i and l in uppercase).\n\n2. **Direct-successor bonus ignores blank lines (2 cases - Halibut, Ogórkowa Zupa)**: The bonus checks the immediately preceding line, but when there's a blank line between the header and title, it fails. I need to scan backward to find the first non-empty line instead.\n\n3. **Roasted Asparagus**: The category header `VEGETABLES` is a single ALL_CAPS word that might become a candidate since it's not in the section labels list, and the title scores lower than the description line. This is another variant of the header-skip problem.\n\n4. **Mushroom Risotto**: `findBurstEnd` can't handle instruction prologues that aren't consecutive. When cooking verbs are interspersed with prose in the spillover, the consecutive-instruction check breaks.\n\n5. **Peach Cobbler**: The overflow marker appears to be corrupted text that's cutting off the analysis.\n\n6. **Mixed-case OCR (Kopytka)**: Erratic capitalization causes the ALL_CAPS path to skip it, and the mixed-case path produces wrong substitutions.\n\nMy improvement plan should address these specific issues: fix the blind OCR repair to handle both `i` and `l` variants contextually, make the direct-successor bonus skip blank lines, broaden the overflow marker detection, handle non-consecutive instruction prologues, and add single-word ALL_CAPS food categories to the section labels.\n\nThere's also a deeper pattern here—all 11 failures stem from the pipeline generating low-confidence garbage instead of returning empty results. I could add a quality gate that rejects candidates below a minimum score threshold, but the user wants a spec that actually solves the root causes, not just masks them. So I'll focus on the targeted fixes and then write up the improvement plan.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5473,"cache_read_input_tokens":59619,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5473},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b1b8cabe-82af-4d43-a6df-d4a8e