{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BoR8exSESZ1qbNLvYLVTyT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see — `VEGETABLES` is in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` but the function `isCategorySectionLabel` is separate from `isSectionLabel`. Let me check if `isCategorySectionLabel` is used in hard filters. Looking at `passesHardFilters`: it calls `isSectionLabel` but probably not `isCategorySectionLabel`. So `VEGETABLES` might pass hard filters.\n\nBut wait — `isSectionLabel` checks `SECTION_LABELS`, not `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. Are they the same? Let me check.\n\nLet me also check if `VEGETABLES` by itself passes hard filters. \n\nSo the single-word filter checks if the text is in `NON_TITLE_WORDS`, and I'm not sure if `vegetables` is in that set. The real question is whether `VEGETABLES` matches the `isSectionLabel` check, which looks at the `SECTION_LABELS` set.\n\nThere are two separate label sets: `SECTION_LABELS` for recipe sections like \"ingredients\" and \"directions\", while `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` contains food categories like \"vegetables\" and \"fish\". Since the hard filter only checks `isSectionLabel` and not the category version, `VEGETABLES` passes through and gets the ALL_CAPS bonus of +0.03. It embeds as \"vegetables\" which is food-related but not a strong recipe title signal.\n\nFor the Roasted Asparagus example, the extractor is picking up the description line starting with \"Simple yet elegant vegetable dish that complements\" — a multi-word phrase that's being considered as a candidate.\n\nWith `FISH & SEAFOOD`, the ampersand doesn't trigger the compound protection, and it likely isn't in `SECTION_LABELS` as a stripped string, so it passes the hard filters and gets the multi-word ALL_CAPS bonus of +0.08. Meanwhile, `Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` is also a candidate, and both are competing for the final selection.\n\nBut the extractor returned `In same pan, sauté shallots until softened` — an instruction line that shouldn't rank higher than either header or title. This suggests the embedding scores might be skewed, or the position bonus is working against the title candidate. If `Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce` is at line 3 but there are many other candidates ahead of it, its `candidateIndex` could be high enough to outweigh its title-like embedding, or it might be filtered out by the pre-filter cap at 25 candidates.\n\nI think I've identified the core issues now. Let me write up a plan with specific fixes targeting these root causes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":495,"cache_read_input_tokens":72417,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":495},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b1b8cabe-82af-4d43-a6df-d4a8ec65d151","uuid":"31cbea35-1f0b-4bcf-957b-bc78b3d8d12d"}
